🛡️ Crack the Gate 1 — picoCTF Detailed Write-Up
📌 Challenge Information

Challenge Name: Crack the Gate 1
Platform: picoCTF
Category: Web Exploitation
Objective: Analyze the login request and retrieve the hidden flag.

This challenge teaches how to analyze HTTP requests and responses using a web proxy tool.

🧰 Tools Used:
1️⃣ Burp Suite Community Edition

Definition:
Burp Suite is a web security testing tool used by penetration testers to intercept, analyze, and modify HTTP requests between a browser and a server.

Why it is used in this challenge:

To intercept login requests

To modify HTTP data

To inspect server responses

🌐 Step 1 — Understand the Target Website
🔎 What we do

Open the challenge instance and inspect how the login page works.

📘 Definition

A login page sends user data (like email or password) to a server using an HTTP request.

📌 Why this matters

If the server does not properly validate the request, it may leak sensitive information.

📡 Step 2 — Intercept the HTTP Request
🔎 What we do

Enable interception in Burp Suite and capture the login request.

Example intercepted request:

POST /login HTTP/1.1
Host: amiable-citadel.picoctf.net:54291
Content-Type: application/json

{
 "email":"ctf-player@picoctf.org"
}
📘 Definition

HTTP Request:
A message sent from a client (browser) to a server asking for an action.

📘 Parts of the request
Part	Meaning
POST	HTTP method used to send data
/login	Endpoint that processes login
Host	Server address
Content-Type	Format of the data (JSON)
Body	Data sent to server
📌 Why this matters

By intercepting the request, we can:

Analyze the data sent to the server

Modify parameters

Replay the request

This is a basic skill in web penetration testing.

🔁 Step 3 — Send Request to Repeater
🔎 What we do

Right-click the intercepted request and select:

Send to Repeater

in Burp Suite.

📘 Definition

Burp Repeater:
A Burp Suite feature that allows you to manually resend HTTP requests multiple times.

📌 Why this is useful

It helps security testers:

Test server responses

Modify request parameters

Identify vulnerabilities

🚀 Step 4 — Replay the Request

Now press Send in the Repeater tab.

The server returns this response:

{
 "success": true,
 "email": "ctf-player@picoctf.org",
 "firstName": "pico",
 "lastName": "player",
 "flag": "picoCTF{brut4_f0rc4_3e21b3a3}"
}
📘 Definition

HTTP Response:
A message sent by the server back to the client after processing a request.

📘 Parts of the response
Part	Meaning
success	Indicates the request worked
email	User email
firstName	User first name
lastName	User last name
flag	Hidden challenge flag
🏁 Step 5 — Capture the Flag

The response directly exposes the flag:

picoCTF{brut4_f0rc4_3e21b3a3}
📘 Definition

Flag:
A secret string hidden in CTF challenges that proves you successfully solved the challenge.

⚠️ Vulnerability Explanation

This challenge demonstrates a security flaw in the API.

Problem

The /login endpoint returns sensitive user data without authentication.

Security Issue

This is an example of:

Broken Authentication

Information Disclosure

Insecure API Design

These issues are listed in the OWASP Top 10 Web Security Risks.

🎓 Key Concepts Learned
Concept	Meaning
HTTP Request	Message sent from client to server
HTTP Response	Server reply to a request
API Endpoint	URL that processes requests
Burp Repeater	Tool to replay HTTP requests
Information Disclosure	Exposure of sensitive data
🧠 Security Lesson

Developers should:

✔ Validate authentication before returning user data
✔ Avoid exposing sensitive fields in API responses
✔ Implement proper access control mechanisms

🏆 Final Result

Flag

picoCTF{brut4_f0rc4_3e21b3a3}

Challenge successfully solved.
